Experiment (b): Build a Simple Web Application using Spring MVC Pattern
This experiment demonstrates the creation of a simple web application using the Spring MVC framework. Spring MVC follows the Model-View-Controller (MVC) design pattern, which separates application logic, user interface, and control flow for better maintainability and scalability.
Aim:
To develop a simple web application following the Model‚ÄìView‚ÄìController (MVC) pattern using the Spring Framework.
Tools Required:
‚Ä¢ JDK 17 or later ‚Äì https://www.oracle.com/java/technologies/javase-downloads.html
‚Ä¢ Apache Tomcat ‚Äì https://tomcat.apache.org/
‚Ä¢ Spring Framework (via Maven)
‚Ä¢ IDE: Eclipse / IntelliJ IDEA / Spring Tool Suite (STS)
‚Ä¢ Maven ‚Äì for project setup and dependency management
Theory:
Spring MVC is a framework that follows the Model‚ÄìView‚ÄìController design pattern:
‚Ä¢ Model ‚Äì Represents the data and business logic.
‚Ä¢ View ‚Äì Defines how the data is presented (HTML/JSP).
‚Ä¢ Controller ‚Äì Handles requests, processes data, and returns views.

Spring MVC Flow:
1. Client sends a request to DispatcherServlet.
2. DispatcherServlet forwards the request to the Controller.
3. Controller interacts with Model and prepares data.
4. DispatcherServlet passes data to the ViewResolver.
5. ViewResolver renders the appropriate view for display.
Procedure:
1. Open Spring Tool Suite (STS) or Eclipse IDE.
2. Create a new Maven project with packaging type WAR.
3. Edit pom.xml to include dependencies for spring-webmvc and servlet-api.
4. Create a Controller class named HomeController.java with @Controller annotation.
5. Map controller to the root URL (/) using @RequestMapping.
6. Add a JSP file (home.jsp) inside WEB-INF/views/ directory.
7. Create dispatcher-servlet.xml configuration file for Spring MVC setup.
8. Add web.xml to define DispatcherServlet mapping.
9. Run the application on Apache Tomcat and verify the output.
Source Code:
pom.xml:
<project xmlns="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0"
         xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
         xsi:schemaLocation="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0
         http://maven.apache.org/xsd/maven-4.0.0.xsd">
  <modelVersion>4.0.0</modelVersion>
  <groupId>com.example</groupId>
  <artifactId>SpringMVCApp</artifactId>
  <version>1.0-SNAPSHOT</version>
  <packaging>war</packaging>

  <dependencies>
    <dependency>
      <groupId>org.springframework</groupId>
      <artifactId>spring-webmvc</artifactId>
      <version>6.1.1</version>
    </dependency>
    <dependency>
      <groupId>javax.servlet</groupId>
      <artifactId>javax.servlet-api</artifactId>
      <version>4.0.1</version>
      <scope>provided</scope>
    </dependency>
  </dependencies>
</project>
HomeController.java:
package com.example.controller;

import org.springframework.stereotype.Controller;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RequestMapping;
import org.springframework.web.servlet.ModelAndView;

@Controller
public class HomeController {

    @RequestMapping("/")
    public ModelAndView homePage() {
        ModelAndView mv = new ModelAndView("home");
        mv.addObject("message", "Welcome to Spring MVC Web Application!");
        return mv;
    }
}
dispatcher-servlet.xml:
<beans xmlns="http://www.springframework.org/schema/beans"
       xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
       xmlns:context="http://www.springframework.org/schema/context"
       xmlns:mvc="http://www.springframework.org/schema/mvc"
       xsi:schemaLocation="
          http://www.springframework.org/schema/beans
          http://www.springframework.org/schema/beans/spring-beans.xsd
          http://www.springframework.org/schema/context
          http://www.springframework.org/schema/context/spring-context.xsd
          http://www.springframework.org/schema/mvc
          http://www.springframework.org/schema/mvc/spring-mvc.xsd">

    <context:component-scan base-package="com.example.controller" />
    <mvc:annotation-driven />

    <bean class="org.springframework.web.servlet.view.InternalResourceViewResolver">
        <property name="prefix" value="/WEB-INF/views/" />
        <property name="suffix" value=".jsp" />
    </bean>

</beans>
home.jsp:
<html>
<head>
    <title>Spring MVC Home</title>
</head>
<body>
    <h2>${message}</h2>
</body>
</html>
web.xml:
<web-app>
    <servlet>
        <servlet-name>dispatcher</servlet-name>
        <servlet-class>org.springframework.web.servlet.DispatcherServlet</servlet-class>
        <load-on-startup>1</load-on-startup>
    </servlet>

    <servlet-mapping>
        <servlet-name>dispatcher</servlet-name>
        <url-pattern>/</url-pattern>
    </servlet-mapping>
</web-app>
Explanation:
‚Ä¢ The pom.xml file defines Maven dependencies for the Spring MVC framework.
‚Ä¢ The HomeController.java file acts as a controller handling incoming requests.
‚Ä¢ The dispatcher-servlet.xml file configures component scanning and view resolution.
‚Ä¢ The home.jsp file represents the view layer, displaying messages from the controller.
‚Ä¢ The web.xml file maps the DispatcherServlet to handle all requests to the application.
Expected Output:
When the project runs, visiting http://localhost:8080/SpringMVCApp/ displays the message:
‚ÄúWelcome to Spring MVC Web Application!‚Äù
Result:
The Spring MVC-based web application was successfully developed and executed, demonstrating the use of the Model‚ÄìView‚ÄìController pattern in Java web development.
